description: TO AMEND H.R. 182, (APP. 2/28/1800), A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR THE ENUMERATION OF THE CITIZENS OF THE UNITED STATES, BY ELIMINATING THE POWER OF DIRECTION ACCORDED THE SECRETARY OF STATE IN THE PURSUANCE OF THE ACT.  (P. 222E

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO REFER TO COMMITTEE THE PETITION OF FREE BLACKS PRAYING FOR A REVISION OF LAWS RELATING TO SLAVE TRADE, BY PROHIBITING LEGISLATION UPON THE SUBJECT WHICH WOULD CREATE DISQUIET AND JEALOUSY.  (P. 244)

TO AGREE WITH THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE NOT TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO REPEAL SO MUCH OF THE ACT PASSED 7/16/1798, AUTHORIZING THE PRESIDENT TO RAISE TWELVE ADDITIONAL REGIMENTS OF INFANTRY.  (P. 369)
TO POSTPONE UNTIL THE NEXT SESSION, THE RESOLUTION TO SUSPEND IN PART, THE ACT TO AUGMENT THE UNITED STATES ARMY, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES.  (P. 403)

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO SUSPEND, IN PART, THE ACT TO AUGMENT THE UNITED STATES ARMY, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES, BY PROVIDING THAT OFFICERS NOT NECESSARY IN THE DISCRETION OF THE PRESIDENT, BE DISCHARGED AND ALLOWED ONE MONTH'S PAY. (P. 403)
TO PASS THE FIRST PART OF THE RESOLUTION TO REPEAL THE SECOND SECTION OF "AN ACT IN ADDITION TO THE ACT FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE UNITED STATES". (P. 419)

TO ADOPT THE SECOND PART OF THE RESOLUTION TO REPEAL THE SECOND SECTION OF "AN ACT IN ADDITION TO THE ACT FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE U.S., WHICH PART MAKES SEDITION PUNISHABLE BY COMMON LAW."  (P. 423)
TO PASS THE ENTIRE RESOLUTION TO REPEAL THE SECOND SECTION OF AN ACT IN ADDITION TO AN ACT FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE U.S.  (P. 425)
TO RECOMMIT THE REPORT CONCERNING THE LETTER FROM MR. RANDOLPH TO THE PRESIDENT RELATING TO A PERSONAL ASSAULT.
TO AMEND THE RANDOLPH RESOLUTIONS TO REPRIMAND CAPTAIN MCKNIGHT AND LIEUTENANT REYNOLDS IN THEIR ACTION AS BEING INDISCREET AND IMPROPER.  (P. K05)
TO AGREE TO THE ORIGINAL AMENDMENT TO THE RANDOLPH RESOLUTIONS THAT SUFFICIENT CAUSE DOES NOT APPEAR FOR THE FURTHER INTERPOSITION OF THIS HOUSE ON THE GROUNDS OF A BREACH OF ITS PRIVILEGES.
TO AGREE TO THE SECOND OF THE RANDOLPH RESOLUTIONS TO EXONERATE CAPTAIN MCKNIGHT AND LIEUTENANT REYNOLDS OF CHARGES OF DISRESPECT TO A MEMBER OF THE HOUSE.  (P. 506)
TO SUSTAIN THE DECISION OF THE CHAIR THAT A NEW RESOLUTION REPRIMANDING MCKNIGHT AND REYNOLDS WAS NOT IN ORDER; DECISION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF THE RANDOLPH RESOLUTIONS.  (P. 507)

TO ORDER THE PREVIOUS QUESTION ON POSTPONEMENT OF THE REPORT OF THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE CONCERNING H.R. 186, (APP. 4/3/1800, 2 STAT 19), A BILL TO ESTABLISH A UNIFORM SYSTEM OF BANKRUPTCY THROUGHTOUT THE UNITED STATES.

TO RECOMMIT H.R. 200, AN ACT IN ADDITION TO THE LAWS RELATIVE TO THE MILITARY ESTABLISHMENT AND CONCERNING ARRESTING SOLDIERS FOR DEBTS, TO A SELECT COMMITTEE WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO ELIMINATE THE EXEMPTION GIVEN TO NON-COMMISSIONED OFFICERS AND OTHERS, FRO ARREST FOR ANY DEBT OR CONTRACT ENTERED INTO BEFORE THEIR ENLISTMENT, ABOVE THE SUM OF $20
TO AMEND H.R. 201, (APP. 2/27/1800), A BILL TO SUSPEND TRADE BETWEEN THE UNITED STATES AND FRANCE, BY PREVENTING ANY NEUTRALS FROM CARRYING ON ANY TRADE FROM THE UNITED STATES WITH FRANCE.  (P. 530)

TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 201 PREVENTING PERSONS RESIDING IN THE WEST INDIES, OR ELSEWHERE EXCEPT EUROPE, WHO OWNED FOREIGN VESSELS, FROM OBTAINING A CLEARANCE BOND TO ANY PORT OF THE FRENCH REPUBLIC.
TO PASS H.R. 201.  (P. 531)
TO PASS H.R. 186, (APP. 4/3/1800, 2 STAT 19), AN ACT TO ESTABLISH A UNIFORM SYSTEM OF BANKRUPTCY THROUGHOUT THE UNITED STATES. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE). (P. 534)
TO DISCHARGE THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE FROM FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION.
TO POSTPONE THE RESOLUTION RELATED TO THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION WHICH CALLS FOR THE RECORD OF THE DISTRICT COURT OF SOUTH CAROLINA OF THE TRIAL OF JONATHAN ROBBINS.
TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION RELATED TO THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION REQUESTING THE RECORDS OF THE TRIAL OF JONATHAN ROBBINS FROM THE DISTRICT COURT OF S. CAROLINA.

TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION TO REQUEST THE PRESIDENT TO SEND THE HOUSE CERTAIN INFORMATION RELATING TO THREE MEN WHO WERE TRIED IN THE NEW JERSEY CIRCUIT COURT ON CHARGES OF PIRACY COMMITTED ON A BRITISH FRIGATE.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO PROCURE INFORMATION REGARDING THE TRIAL OF THREE MEN IN THE NEW JERSEY CIRCUIT COURT ON CHARGES OF PIERACY COMMITTED ON A BRITISH FRIGATE.  (SPEAKER VOTING NAY.)
TO DETERMINE IF THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE HOUSE SHALL HAVE PERMISSION TO DISCUSS THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION AGAIN AFTER VOTING AGAINST ITS PASSAGE.
TO AGREE WITH THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE TO REJECT THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION.  (P. 619)
TO DISCHARGE THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE FROM FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF THE ROBBINS RESOLUTION.  (P. 621)
TO AMEND H.R. 208, A BILL FOR THE BETTER GOVERNMENT OF THE MARINE CORPS WHILE ON SHORE, BY ELIMINATING THE PROVISION THAT OFFICERS VIOLATING THIS ACT WILL BE TRIED IN A COURT OF LAW.  (P. 624)

TO CONCUR IN THE REPORT OF THE COMMITTEE CONCERNING H.R. 218 (APP. 5/10/1800), AN ACT SUPPLEMENTARY TO THE ACT ENTITLED "AN ACT FOR AN AMICABLE SETTLEMENT OF THE LIMITS OF THE STATE OF GEORGIA AND FOR AUTHORIZING THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A GOVERNMENT IN THE ISSISSIPPI TERRITORY
TO PASS H.R. 210, (APP. 5/2/1800), AN ACT TO ENABLE THE PRESIDENT TO BORROW MONEY FOR THE PUBLIC SERVICE FOR NO MORE THAN $3,500,000.  (P. 633)
TO PASS THE COMPLIMENTARY RESOLUTION FOR GALLANTRY AND GOOD CONDUCT OF CAPTAIN TRUXTUN, AND PRESENTATION OF A GOLD MEDAL IN RECOGNITION OF SAID SERVICE.  (P. 642)
TO PASS H.R. 222, (APP. 5/16/1800), A BILL TO SETTLE THE CLAIM FOR USE, OCCUPATION AND DAMAGE DONE TO THE RHODE ISLAND COLLEGE BY UNITED STATES TROOPS. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE).
TO POSTPONE H.R. 215, A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR THE BETTER ESTABLISHMENT OF THE COURTS OF THE UNITED STATES, UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY IN DECEMBER.
TO POSTPONE H.R. 215 UNTIL THE NEXT SESSION.  (P. 648)

TO POSTPONE H.R. 225, (APP. 4/28/1800, 2 STAT 56), A BILL TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO ACCEPT A CESSION OF JURISDICTION OF TERRITORY LYING WEST OF PENNSYLVANIA, COMMONLY CALLED THE WESTERN RESERVE OF CONNECTICUT.  (P. 658)

TO POSTPONE H.R. 193, (APP. 4/12/1800), A BILL TO CONTINUE IN FORCE, AN ACT CONCERNING CERTAIN FISHERIES OF THE UNITED STATES, FOR THE GOVERNMENT OF THE FISHERMEN EMPLOYED THEREIN, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES.  (P. 659)

TO PASS H.R. 225, (APP. 4/28/1800, 2 STAT 56), A BILL TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO ACCEPT A CESSION OF JURISDICTION OF THE TERRITORY WEST OF PENNSYLVANIA, COMMONLY CALLED THE WESTERN RESERVE OF CONNECTICUT.  (P. 662)
TO POSTPONE H.R. 215.  (P. 666)
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION TO CONTINUE IN FORCE AN ACT LAYING AN ADDITIONAL DUTY ON IMPORTED SALT, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES.
TO POSTPONE S. 58, A BILL PRESCRIBING THE MODE OF DECIDING DISPUTED ELECTIONS OF PRESIDENT AND VICE PRESIDENT. (P. 674)
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO CONTINUE IN FORCE AN ACT LAYING AN ADDITIONAL DUTY ON IMPORTED SALT, BY REDUCING THE DURATION OF SAID ACT TO A TERM OF TWO YEARS RATHER THAN 10 YEARS.  (P. 675)
TO POSTPONE H.R. 253, A BILL FOR APPOINTMENT OF ADMIRALS IN THE NAVY.  (P. 676)

TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 218, (APP. 5/10/1800), A BILL SUPPLEMENTAL TO THE ACT FOR AN AMICABLE SETTLEMENT OF LIMITS WITHIN THE STATE OF GEORGIA, AND AUTHORIZING THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A GOVERNMENT IN THE MISSISSIPPI TERRITORY; SAID AMENDMET TO ELIMINATE THAT PART OF THE BILL WHICH ABROGATES THE POWER OF THE GOVERNOR TO PROROGUE THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY AT HIS PLEASURE.

TO CONCUR WITH THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE IN THEIR DISAGREEMENT TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 218, (APP. 5/10/1800), A BILL CONCERNING SETTLEMENT OF LIMITS WITHIN GEORGIA AND A MISSISSIPPI GOVERNMENT; SAID AMENDMENT WOULD AUTHORIZE THE COMMISSIONERS TOSETTLE INDIVIDUAL CLAIMS
TO POSTPONE H.R. 221, A BILL TO ESTABLISH A MILITARY ACADEMY, AND FOR THE BETTER ORGANIZATION OF THE CORPS OF ARTILLERISTS AND ENGINEERS.  (P. 690)

TO AMEND AN AMENDMENT TO S. 58, BY ELIMINATING THE PROVISION THAT THE HOUSE AND SENATE CHOOSE BY BALLOT, FOUR MEMBERS TO FORM A COMMITTEE HAVING POWER TO INVESTIGATE DISPUTES OTHER THAN SUCH AS MAY RELATE TO THE NUMBER OF VOTES.  (P. 694)
TO AMEND AN AMENDMENT TO S. 58, BY PROVIDING TO SETTLE ANY DISAGREEING QUESTIONS OF THE JOINT COMMITTEE BY TAKING A YEA AND NAY VOTE.
TO PASS S. 58.  (P. 697)
TO PASS H.R. 247, A BILL TO AMEND THE ACT TO PROHIBIT CARRYING ON THE SLAVE TRADE TO ANY FOREIGN COUNTRY. (P. 699)
TO CONCUR WITH THE COMMITTEE TO PASS THE HOUSE RESOLUTION TO LAY AN ADDITIONAL DUTY ON IMPORTED BROWN SUGAR.
TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO S. 58 WHICH CHANGES THE WORD "REJECTING" TO "ADMITTING," THUS CHANGING THE PRINCIPLE OF THE BILL.  (P. 710)
TO PASS H.R. 268, A BILL TO ERECT A MAUSOLEUM FOR PRESIDENT WASHINGTON, IN THE CITY OF WASHINGTON.  (P. 712)

TO AMEND S. 63 (APP. 5/14/1800), A BILL SUPPLEMENTARY TO THE ACT TO AUGMENT THE ARMY; BY ELIMINATING THE RESPONSIBILITY IMPOSED ON THE PRESIDENT TO WAIT UNTIL THE PRELIMINARIES OF PEACE WERE SIGNED WITH FRANCE, THEREBY DISCHARGING THE ADDITIONAL ARMY NOW  (P

TO CONCUR WITH THE COMMITTEE TO AMEND S. 63, (APP. 5/14/1800), A BILL SUPPLEMENTARY TO THE ACT TO AUGMENT THE ARMY, BY ALLOWING ONE MONTHS PAY MORE AS COMPENSATION FOR SERVICES AND EXPENSES IN RETURNING HOME. (P. 714)
TO AGREE TO THE REPLY OF THE COMMITTEE TO THE PRESIDENT'S SPEECH IN RELATION TO NEGOTIATIONS WITH FRANCE.  (P. 791)

TO AGREE TO THE REPORT OF THE SELECT COMMITTEE THAT IT IS NOT EXPEDIENT FOR THE HOUSE TO MAKE ANY ORDER GRANTING PERMISSION TO REPORTERS TO BE ADMITTED WITHIN THE BAR. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE).
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO REDUCE THE SECOND REGIMENT OF ARTILLERY FROM FOUR TO THREE BATTALIONS.  (P. 835)

TO AMEND A MEMORIAL OF THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE MISSISSIPPI TERRITORY ON THE OFFICIAL CONDUCT OF GOVERNOR SARGENT IN ENACTING UNCONSTITUTIONAL LAWS IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE JUDGES OF SAID TERRITORY, BY APPOINTING A COMMITTEE TO INVESTIGATE THE ATTER, WITH AUTHORITY TO SEND FOR PERSONS AND PAPERS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF H.R. 270, A BILL TO ERECT A MAUSOLEUM TO GEORGE WASHINGTON.  (P. 864)
TO PASS H.R. 270.

TO COMMIT THE RESOLUTION TO EXTEND AN ACT IN ADDITION TO THE ACT ENTITLED "AN ACT FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE UNITED STATES" PASSED JULY 14, 1798, TO THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE HOUSE.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT IT IS NOT EXPEDIENT TO TAKE FURTHER ACTION CONCERNING THE LETTER OF JOSEPH WHEATON, SERGEANT-AT-ARMS, RELATING TO HIS ARREST.
TO RECONSIDER THE VOTE TO PASS THE PRIVILEGE RESOLUTION.
TO PASS THE PRIVILEGE RESOLUTION.  (P. 890)
TO AMEND H.R. 275, A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR THE MORE CONVENIENT ORGANIZATION OF THE COURTS, BY DEFINING BOUNDARIES WITH RELATION TO COURT DISTRICTS FOR THE EASTERN AND WESTERN DISTRICTS OF VIRGINIA.

TO AMEND H.R. 275, BY FIXING A MINIMUM SUM OF $400 IN ANY ACTION OR SUIT AGAINST ANY ALIEN OR CITIZEN, IN ANY STATE AS THE MINIMUM AMOUNT BY WHICH A PLAINTIFF CAN LAWFULLY FILE A PETITION TO A CIRCUIT COURT FOR A HEARING AND DECISION OF SAID COURT.
TO AMEND AN AMENDMENT TO H.R. 275 TO INCLUDE PROMISSORY NOTES AND BONDS, PAYABLE TO ORDER OR ASSIGNS AS AN EXCEPTION TO THE CONDITIONS OF THE BILL.  (P. 908)
TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 275 TO LEAVE THE JURISDICTION OF THE FEDERAL COURTS, AS IT NOW STANDS.

TO AMEND H.R. 276, A BILL TO CONTINUE IN FORCE THE ACTS LAYING DUTIES ON LICENSES FOR SELLING WINES AND FOREIGN DISTILLED SPIRITS BY RETAIL, ON PROPERTY SOLD AT AUCTION, AND ON CARRIAGES FOR THE CONVEYANCE OF PERSONS, BY PUTTING A TIME LIMIT ON THE DURATON OF THE BILL TO MAR

TO PASS H.R. 276, A BILL TO CONTINUE IN FORCE THE ACTS LAYING DUTIES ON LICENSES FOR SELLING WINES AND FOREIGN DISTILLED SPIRITS, ON PROPERTY SOLD AT AUCTION, AND ON CARRIAGES FOR THE CONVEYANCE OF PERSONS.  (P. 911)
TO PASS H.R. 275.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO CONTINUE IN FORCE THE ACT COMMONLY CALLED THE SEDITION LAW. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE).  (P. 975)
TO PASS H.R. 279, A BILL TO DISCHARGE SAMUEL LEWIS FROM HIS IMPRISONMENT.  (P. 978)
TO PASS H.R. 281, A BILL TO INCORPORATE THE PERSONS THEREIN NAMED, AND THEIR ASSOCIATES, AS A MINE AND METAL COMPANY. (P. 989)

TO DISAGREE WITH THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE IN THEIR AGREEMENT TO THE FOURTH RULE OF THE REPORT OF A SPECIAL COMMITTEE CONCERNING RULES PROPER TO BE OBSERVED IN THE ELECTION OF A PRESIDENT; SAID RULE STATES THAT "AFTER COMMENCING THE BALLOTING FOR PRESIDNT, THE HOUSE SHALL NOT ADJOURN UNTIL A CHOICE IS MADE."  (P

TO DISAGREE WITH THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE IN THEIR AGREEMENT TO THE FIFTH RULE OF THE COMMITTEE REPORT CONCERNING RULES TO BE OBSERVED IN THE ELECTION OF THE PRESIDENT; SAID RULE STATES THAT THE DOORS OF THE HOUSE BE CLOSED DURING THE BALLOTING, EXCEPTAGAINST THE OFFICERS OF THE HOUSE
TO POSTPONE UNTIL MONDAY, H.R. 302, A BILL TO CONTINUE IN FORCE AN ACT FURTHER TO SUSPEND THE COMMERCIAL INTERCOURSE BETWEEN THE UNITED STATES AND FRANCE AND THE DEPENDENCIES THEREOF.  (P. 1019)
TO REJECT H.R. 302, A BILL TO EXTEND THE SUSPENSION OF COMMERCIAL INTERCOURSE WITH FRANCE.

TO AGREE TO ADD AN ADDITIONAL RULE IN RELATION TO THE PRESIDENTAL ELECTION: THAT 600 TICKETS BE PRINTED ON WHICH WOULD BE THE NAME THOMAS JEFFERSON OF VIRGINIA, AND 600 TICKETS BE PRINTED ON WHICH WOULD BE THE NAME AARON BURR OF NEW YORK".  (P. 1022)
TO REJECT H.R. 309, A BILL TO REPEAL PART OF THE SEDITION ACT, AND TO CONTINUE IN FORCE THE RESIDUE OF THE SAME. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE NEGATIVE).

TO DECIDE IF THE MOTION TO TAKE UP A RESOLUTION IS IN ORDER; SAID RESOLUTION STATES THAT THE SPEAKER HAS ASSUMED A POWER NOT HIS, IN DIRECTING THE EXPULSION OF SAMUEL HARRISON SMITH FROM THE GALLERY OF THE HOUSE.
TO SUSTAIN THE DECISION OF THE CHAIR TO CALL A MEMBER OF THE HOUSE TO ORDER.
TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION THAT THE POWER OF THE SPEAKER, OR CHAIRMAN OF THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, SHALL NOT BE CONSTRUED TO EXTEND (EXCEPT IN SPECIFIC SITUATIONS) TO THE EXPULSION OF ANY PERSON.

TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 309, A BILL TO REPEAL PART OF AN ACT ENTITLED "AN ACT IN ADDITION TO THE ACT ENTITLED "AN ACT FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE UNITED STATES' AND TO CONTINUE IN FORCE THE RESIDUE OF THE SAME"  (P
TO PASS S. 68, AN ACT CONCERNING THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA. (P. 1052)

TO AMEND H.R. 306, A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR A NAVAL PEACE ESTABLISHMENT AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES, BY ELIMINATING THE SECTION TO PAY CERTAIN OFFICERS HALF THEIR MONTHLY PAY IF UNEMPLOYED UPON THE REDUCTION OF THE NAVY, ON CERTAIN CONDITIONS.  (P. 1057)
TO AMEND H.R. 306, BY GIVING THE PRESIDENT AUTHORITY TO DISCHARGE ANY PART OF THE MARINE CORPS WHICH MAY BE UNNECESSARY FOR THE NAVAL SERVICE.  (P. 1057)
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 306. (P. 1058)
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 291, A BILL TO AMEND AND CONTINUE IN FORCE "AN ACT TO ESTABLISH A UNIFORM SYSTEM OF BANKRUPTCY THROUGHOUT THE UNITED STATES".
TO PASS H.R. 306.  (P. 1061)

TO RECOMMIT THE FOURTH SECTION OF H.R. 291, AN ACT TO AMEND AND CONTINUE IN FORCE "AN ACT TO ESTABLISH A UNIFORM SYSTEM OF BANKRUPTCY THROUGHOUT THE UNITED STATES," TO COMMITTEE FOR RECONSIDERATION AND DISCUSSION.
TO AMEND THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 270, IN ORDER TO INCREASE THE AMOUNT APPROPRIATED.  (P. 1071)
TO AGREE TO CERTAIN AMENDMENTS TO H.R. 270 THAT WERE MADE AT THE CLERKS DESK.
TO AGREE TO THE RESOLUTION TO AUTHORIZE THE CLERK OF THE HOUSE TO PAY TO THE DOORKEEPER AND SERGEANT OF ARMS $200 EACH FOR EXTRA SERVICES.  (P. 1074)
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT THERE DOES NOT APPEAR CAUSE FOR FURTHER PROCEEDINGS ON THE MATTER OF COMPLAINT FOR MALADMINISTRATION AGAINST WINTHROP SARGEANT, GOVERNOR OF THE MISSISSIPPI TERRITORY.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT THE THANKS OF THE HOUSE BE PRESENTED TO THEODORE SEDGWICK FOR HIS CONDUCT AS SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE.  (P. 1079)
